Apologies for the confusion. To label the right-angled triangle properly, we can modify the HTML code to add labels to the appropriate sides of the triangle.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <style>
        .triangle {
            width: 0;
            height: 0;
            border-left: 100px solid transparent;
            border-bottom: 100px solid black;
            position: relative;
            top: 50px;
            left: 50px;
        }

        .labels {
            display: flex;
            justify-content: center;
            align-items: center;
            position: relative;
            top: -20px;
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            font-size: 14px;
            font-weight: bold;
        }

        .labels .label {
            margin: 5px;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div class="triangle"></div>
    <div class="labels">
        <div class="label">125 cm</div>
        <div class="label">250 cm (Ramp)</div>
        <div class="label">30°</div>
    </div>
</body>
</html>
```

In this updated HTML code, we have positioned the right-angled triangle using the `top` and `left` CSS properties. The labels are added below the triangle using the `.labels` class, and each label is placed inside a `div` with the `.label` class. The labels are centered using flexbox alignment properties.

Feel free to adjust the `top` and `left` values in the `.triangle` style to position the triangle relative to the page according to your preference.
